We’ve been following Dee Clements of @studio_herron’s career for a long time — from her gorgeous woven textiles to the rug she designed for Land of Nod (RIP) to her baby steps into basketry. But her work truly blossomed when she began working with @thefutureperfect during the pandemic. Her baskets grew in size and scope, mirroring both her personal and professional growth, and they began incorporating not only hand-dyed reeds but also painterly brushstrokes that hearken back to how Clements began her career: as a painter. When we were discussing Clements’s inclusion in this list, we said, “Bet she’s working on lighting next” — turns out we were right, and we can’t wait to see the results. ⁠
⁠
"I’m seeing in American design right now a sweet spot between art, craft, and design that elevates the quotidian into something dramatic, or magical, or exuberant. Namely, furniture and objects that mix typologies and/or materials to bring out fresh perspectives on the designed and built world. I am also seeing work by more women and people of color and that truly excites me! I want marginalized voices to have a seat at the table and a place in the spotlight." #americandesignhotlist

This is my new girl Frieda! She was a stray roaming the mean streets of Benton Harbor, MI. Animal control picked her up and put her in their dog shelter where she’s been since December 16, 2022. No one came to get her and she wasn’t microchipped.
I found her on “dog tinder” aka Petfinder and swiped right! Drove over to Michigan yesterday to meet her. I walked into the room and she crawled right into my lap and snuggled. Yup! You guessed it! My heart swelled so big it overtook my whole body and well, I just died right away. So we’ve known each other for 28 hours now and basically we’re in love. She barfed 6 x in the car on the drive back to Chicago and on the way to my studio today but that’s part of us getting to know each other. I guess she’s a homebody at heart who gets car sick, just like me. I can’t believe no one else wanted to adopt her. She’s such a smart, playful, snuggly, perfect love-bug. Somewhere between ages 2 and 5, Rat Terrier mix. Keep thinking I might call her Georgia, but also love the name Frieda, which is the name the animal shelter gave her. I’m so happy we’re in each others lives now, so much so that I just wanna hang with her and teach her stuff and not do my work. Welcome to the pack Miss Frieda or Georgia.😍

“Hystero”, (ceramic, reed, paint/dye, 32”-26.5”) it’s the Ancient Greek word for womb or uterus. It is also a derivative of the word Hysteria- which means a sudden emotional outburst characterized by irrationality. It’s no coincidence that the etymology of Hystero and Hysteria are linked. The ancient Greeks believed hysteria was a problem particular to women, originating from the woman’s uterus. 
This hysterical Hystero is on view now @65grand in Chicago throughout March.

Nina Johnson is pleased to present The Future has an Ancient Heart, a solo exhibition of all new works by artist Dee Clements opening June 1st in the Exhibition Library. The show centers around years of research on paleolithic weaving traditions, specifically shedding light on women’s roles in craft and their historically neglected, unseen labor through the lenses of feminism, ethnography, and patriarchy.

Interested in the connections between history, culture, and contemporary art, Clements’ practice visually examines the societal roles women have been relegated to, and recontextualizes crafts deemed as “women’s work,” which historically include needle work, sewing, and weaving. The title of the exhibition, The Future has an Ancient Heart, is a line borrowed from writer, painter, and activist Carlo Levi. Similar to the quote, Clements’ work charges forward while reflecting on the past, tracing the lineage of craft and patriarchy to their earliest origins.

The Future has an Ancient Heart will be on view from June 1st - July 29th, 2023.

Dee Clements
Woman Seated, 2023
Reed, dye, gouache paint, spray paint, ceramic, polyurethane
35” h x 29” dia.

Opening tomorrow in the Exhibition Library, Dee Clement’s first solo show with the gallery: The Future has an Ancient Heart.

The Future has an Ancient Heart features a new body of the artist’s signature large-scale woven baskets and sculptural works, all realized within the last 3 years.

I was driving to FedEx today to ship stuff and I was lost in thought about what it means to be in your second act in life. The second 30 years. How the body changes and priorities and attitudes shift. It’s all informed by our early selves, our childhood experiences. The works in my show lean and slump, have lumps and rolls, pudge and dimple. It takes so long for humans to settle into themselves and that’s something on my mind these days. I’m almost always looking backward in order to move forward.

Back at work today. It’s good to be home. I’m a much better human when my dog is close by me. Anyway, I’m back from time near Aspen teaching basketry. Thinking about privilege, class and equity quite a lot. Viola Davis was recently on the cover of Architectural Digest. When I saw that I exclaimed HELL YEAH! I read her memoir twice, hanging on every single word. She had a really fraught childhood. I too was recently in Architectural Digest, and the personal significance of that was not lost on me. I too had a fraught childhood and spent some time in late teenage/early adulthood homeless. Those were some scrappy, brutal years. Yeah. Just thinking about privilege, class and equity and all the complexities that lie in-between. Chameleon-ing between worlds and all that stuff. It’s probably gonna be a weird day in my brain today.😵‍💫
My show, The Future Has an Ancient Heart is in view through July 29 @ninajohnsongallery in Miami in the Exhibition Library.💕

‘Woman Seated’, one of several sculptures on view @ninajohnsongallery . The form language of each piece in this solo presentation reflects on the unseen labor of women through vessel-like forms, which also reference the human body, more specifically the female body for its miraculous ability give and sustain life. These works are handwoven, dyed, painted and incorporate, at times, ceramic bases. The bowl atop ‘Woman Seated’ is also part of an early theme regarding highlighting small, more precious craft objects. It felt right to combine some of these ideas here.

I’m working on 3 giant sculptures for @sirenbettydesign that will encase 3 architectural pillars in a space in Chicago. The weaving is fabricated on powder coated steel armatures in two halves per piece. (Thanks to @olive_pits  for designing and fabricating these steel armatures for me!) These sculptures are my most ambitious and large scale works to date, I’ve been excited to scale up and challenge myself! Though my progress has been slow, punctuated by body injuries (my poor worn rotator cuff), teaching and lecture engagements scheduled well before this project came my way and in a few weeks a move of my whole studio and home that will slow my work schedule even more. I have felt like I’m moving through mud trying to carve out steady, solid studio time in the past month and a half and learning too the word NO is a complete sentence. I’m looking for a new studio assistant to help me get these biggies done on schedule and posted some details in my stories. 🆘🛟 Or if you know how I can clone myself or magically grow 2 heads and 16 arms, I’m all ears. 😂

Plugging along on these giant architectural pillar sculptures. 1.5 of 3 in progress for a @sirenbettydesign project in Chicago.😅 Def turn sound off unless you want to hear me aggressively nose breathing.

Almost half way done with these giant 3D woven sculptures made from dyed and painted rattan and powdercoated stainless steel. Each are 4ft tall made in two halves each, with a 4 ft diameter. They’ll be installed around 3 interior architectural pillars, two halves that will install to be one. A commission through @sirenbettydesign . This project has been punctuated by a serious shoulder injury that isn’t healing, teaching engagements across the country and in a week, a giant move of both my studio and home to new spaces. Im so eager to get these biggies installed in a few short weeks. Thank you to @abbeymuza without them, nothing would get done this summer and I would probably die.

This summer has been a bear.  Moving is stirring up all kinds of muck. There’s intense traffic, smokey air, unbearable heat to name a few things. The city feels particularly intense this summer, and aggro. As soon as I can afford to buy a house, which will probably be never, I’m trading it all in for country roads, cows as neighbors and clear fresh water. Raise your hand if you too are having intense environmental and existential dread. 

Here’s a pic of the new studio I’ve been working on getting ready. That whole process has been another kind of bear. A big ol grizzly one. It doesn’t feel as good as I’d hoped. Fingers crossed it’ll be a nice landing place for the time in between now and my country fantasy.

Next month I’ll be teaching a weaving workshop with craft students at @oficioscreativos_uct - Universidad Católica de Temuco in Chilé invited by Piedad Aguilar, head of the textile area of the new BA Creative Crafts.
We will be working with plant fibers native to the region; Pita pictured here and ñocha and mimbre, all of which are new to me. We’ll be discussing the Carrier Bag Theory and working on exercises with the fiber in relation to this theory and the natural landscape. I’m very honored to be invited and really looking forward to this opportunity. I love learning about fibers unfamiliar to me and how we can apply them to the designed and built world. Thank you Piedad!!!

They’re done!!! These giant sculptures will be installed this week, at a private space in Chicago via @sirenbettydesign. Each piece is made in two halves that will encase 3 architectural pillars. This project has taken almost 8 months and I’m grateful to @abbeymuza and @sculpturelandia for their production help. I can’t believe we are at the finish line. 😅 During this project I also built two solo gallery shows, taught two long form residency style workshops, moved my studio (and my house) and blew out my shoulder. Wow! What a year!

Three sculptures finished and installed on Labor Day weekend. The largest works I’ve ever made, and couldn’t have done it w/o @abbeymuza @sculpturelandia @__claytonphillips__ @rufinoqjimenez I am really proud of this work and grateful for the opportunity to make it and the help to bring it to life.

I’ll be working on this holiday, to finish the last part of this project. Which reminds me to wish everyone a Happy Labor Day! This is an important holiday that honors the labor movement. Established by labor organizers in the 19th century. My parents were (mom) a housekeeper-bus driver-truck driver-waitress-hostess-bartender and (dad) a V.A worker-home health equipment delivery person-sports equipment manager. I grew up going to work with my mom when there was no school. I have vivid memories of playing in a restaurant basement where she laundered and ironed table linens. Today, I think about all the people who put up the drywall and hang the lights, and clean the spaces of all the rooms my artwork hangs, including this room. I think about how this holiday, like all American holidays, are now largely focused on holiday sales and getting more stuff for cheap. Which means we’re all out there hustling to make a living. And that’s a bigger kind of issue. Ahem-capitalism. Anyway, happy Labor Day and thank you to all and especially to the working class folks, without them, our society would probably fall to pieces.

Next week I’ll have been in this space for one month. Wow! Time is speeding by. I still have so many boxes to unpack, shelves to put up and much organizing to do. The landlord doesn’t know yet but I’ll probably royally eff up these floors. I just finished my biggest project ever amidst all this chaos, and already on to the next one.  I don’t think I’ve ever said this in the history of my life, but I’m glad summer is over and the crisp coolness of fall is on its way. Makes me feel like I’m not in a pressure cooker anymore. Thanks a million b’jillion to @abbeymuza who helped me so much this summer.

Thoughts on weeds: Yes, the errant plants that spring up in the garden or along the patches of green on the side of the road. My attentions have been all over the place for months. I call that ‘Life weeds’. Which are things that divert and punctuate your energy and attentions away from your main focus. Yesterday was the first full studio day I’ve had in months without life weeds, to focus on a new body of work without meetings or appointments and that uninterrupted time is the garden bounty right there. The happy place. The sense of home. 🌿🪻🌱🌼 (Ok that and being surrounded by beautiful plants.)

It’s been truly wonderful to teach design students at Universidad Catholica de Temuco in Temuco Chilé! I’ve had the most amazing experience here.

27 international artists, designers and architects were invited to come and teach individual week-long workshops @oficioscreativos_uct , @faad_uct that all students in the school of art and design could participate in. My workshop included students from architecture, design and craft, exploring relationships through 3D form and the craft of weaving. We used foraged local materials: Mimbre and Pita, which were new to me. The students had never before done any kind of weaving, and the results of the class were incredible. They all made such interesting, thoughtful work and were the loveliest young people I have ever met. They give me hope for the future. Getting to this beautiful countryside town took an exhausting 27 hours, but my time here has been filled with warmth, kindness, joy, abundance, creativity and new friendships. Thank you for sharing your lives, language, food, homes and culture with me.

“These days, being an artist is a political act, no matter what kind of art you make.” Artist Annabeth Rosen said that. I had the immense privilege of hearing her lecture at her @cranbrookartmuseum exhibition a few years back when I was a grad student @cranbrook_art in 3D Design. I’m a BIG fan girl of Rosen’s work. She studied at Cranbrook along side Laura Foster Nicholson and Ben Nicholson, whom I was an artist assistant to in my 20s and felt such love for them as artists. They all graduated from Cranbrook together when I was just born and the network of roots that often feels familial at Cranbrook is also so complex. I keep thinking about Annabeth’s sentence above and my feelings about recent political events at the school, and worldwide. I have so much to say yet I can’t seem to find the words to make sense of my complicated and devastated feelings about the war, wealth, class, privilege, religion, education. The feelings are big, deeply unsettled, helpless. So I’m doing the only thing I’ve ever known how to do, making work in the studio to express what my words can’t. Art is power. Remember that. ❤️
Some niceness from the last 30 days. 🍂

It’s Thanksgiving. My (half) sister Rae passed away this month from an aggressive form of cancer. She was 51. We didn’t really know each other, she graduated high school when I was 10 years old and we grew up in separate towns and really, separate family’s too. Rae’s passing is deeply painful to me even though we were virtually strangers to each other. It is indicative of a larger pain. The lovely thing is, I have 3 chosen sisters: Robin, Gretchen, Annie. My dearests who are a trifecta of love and wisdom. What abundance! A few months back, my sister told me to “live my best life” because of the short time we all have here. It reminded me of this phrase from Sri Nisargadatta: Love tells me I’m everything, wisdom tells me I’m nothing, between the two my life flows.
Happy day of thanks and giving. I know I’m doing both of those today. RIP Rachelle, your life was meaningful and now you are in the boundlessness of time and space.🤍🕊️🕯️

Work-in-progress sneak peek:

‘Yes Is a Pleasant Country’ 
is the title of my newest body of work, comprised of 10 new woven/ceramic sculptures to be presented in Feb/March 2024 at The Felix Art Fair (@felixartfair ) in Los Angeles with the incomparable Nina Johnson Gallery (@ninajohnsongallery ).

The title comes from the E.E. 
Cummings poem of the same name, alluding to the idea that positivity is a state of mind, the journey to life’s ease and sweetness is rife with obstacle, but saying yes to challenge  and opportunity is part of the journey in embracing life and living shiningly in the present. 

This is the 3rd body of work I’ve made for solo presentation in 12 months. During its creation, I tore my left rotator cuff (I’m still injured) my estranged sister died (I’m grieving the strangest dislocated familial grief), I hit a rather rocky financial patch this month (yay! a perimenopausal depression landmine). Yes IS a pleasant country! While my heart is a bruised peach these past weeks, I keep saying YES to this creative practice that I feel deeply compelled to do, thereby saying YES to myself. Even when it brings me despair and life throws me rotten lemons. I can find my way back to joy and deep knowing through it—-art is for the human spirit. It’s a channel to FEEL alive. These works are that.

I am proud to present this new body of work and couldn’t be more grateful for the opportunity to share it with the world with a gallery team I trust and respect. 💥
Thx NJG: Nina, Karina, Fran, Julie, Nati, Mia.💛 I’m so grateful for you all.
